-- NEITHER view, and getProjectDetail's `LEFT JOIN lorries l1 ON l1.id =
-- p.setup_lorry_id` (services/projects.ts) 500s on EVERY project there. Same
-- class as the "scm PL/pgSQL restored out-of-band, not in the tree" trap; PR
-- #674 (scm schema blueprint) is the strategic fix. This migration captures the
-- two specific views so the tree is self-consistent.
--
-- HOW TO COMPLETE THIS FILE (DO NOT hand-write the bodies from imagination — a
-- drifted column would 500 and block ALL deploys; the DB is ground truth):
--   1. Run the "Dump public compat views (read-only)" workflow
--      (.github/workflows/dump-compat-views.yml) against prod (or staging if the
--      views are present there too).
--   2. Copy each `pg_get_viewdef` body verbatim into the two CREATE OR REPLACE
--      VIEW statements below, replacing the <<< PASTE ... >>> placeholder.
--   3. Rename this file: drop the `.TEMPLATE` suffix so it becomes `.sql`.
--   4. Confirm the splitter contract (see below) still holds, then commit.
--
-- SPLITTER CONTRACT (scripts/pg-migrate.mjs splits the file on /;\s*\n/):
--   - Each statement's ONLY `;` must be the final one, on its own line's end.
--   - No dollar-quoted bodies, no internal `;\n`. A plain SELECT-based view body
--     from pg_get_viewdef satisfies this (its single terminating `;` is added by
--     the CREATE OR REPLACE below). See 0106_report_views_company_id.sql for a
--     worked example of pasting pg_get_viewdef bodies under this contract.
--
-- IDEMPOTENCY / SAFETY: CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW is safe on an env where the view
-- already exists AS LONG AS the captured column set matches (CREATE OR REPLACE
-- only permits appending columns) — which it will, because we capture the exact
-- prod body. On a fresh env it simply creates the view. The views reference
-- scm.trips / scm.lorries, so scm.* must be present first (same dependency
-- 0106 already relies on; PR #674 formalises it).
--
-- search_path pinned so the (already fully-qualified) scm.* refs resolve and the
-- views land in public.

